04827nam a22007215i 9780231537742DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014000748  a97802315377427 a10.7312/scap164322doi  a(DE-B1597)458494  a(OCoLC)979683185  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN56.3.V4bS38 2014 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aScappettone, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKilling the Moonlight :bModernism in Venice /cJennifer Scappettone. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b‹B›44 b&w illus; 17 color illus.‹/B›  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Venetian Modernity: A Troubled Present -- t1. “The Entanglement of Memory”: Reciprocal Interference of Present and Past in Ruskin’s Venetian Histories -- t2. Nearer Distances and Clearer Mysteries: Between Patches and Presence in James’s “Visitable Past” -- t3. Adriatic Fantasies: Venetian Modernism Between Decadence, Futurism, and the World Wars -- t4. From Passéism to Anachronism: Material Histories in Pound’s Venice -- t5. Fabulous Planning: Unbuilt Venices -- tCoda: Laguna/Lacuna -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs a city that seems to float between Europe and Asia, removed by a lagoon from the tempos of terra firma, Venice has long seduced the Western imagination. Since the 1797 fall of the Venetian Republic, fantasies about the sinking city have engendered an elaborate series of romantic clichés, provoking conflicting responses: some modern artists and intellectuals embrace the resistance to modernity manifest in Venice's labyrinthine premodern form and temporality, whereas others aspire to modernize by "killing the moonlight" of Venice, in the Futurists' notorious phrase.Spanning the history of literature, art, and architecture—from John Ruskin, Henry James, and Ezra Pound to Manfredo Tafuri, Italo Calvino, Jeanette Winterson, and Robert Coover—Killing the Moonlight tracks the pressures that modernity has placed on the legacy of romantic Venice, and the distinctive strains of aesthetic invention that resulted from the clash. In Venetian incarnations of modernism, the anachronistic urban fabric and vestigial sentiment that both the nation-state of Italy and the historical avant-garde would cast off become incompletely assimilated parts of the new. Killing the Moonlight brings Venice into the geography of modernity as a living city rather than a metaphor for death, and presents the archipelago as a crucible for those seeking to define and transgress the conceptual limits of modernism. In strategic detours from the capitals of modernity, the book redrafts the confines of modernist culture in both geographical and historical terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiterature, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Aesthetics) 0aModernism (Aesthetics). 0aModernism (Literature) 0aModernism (Literature). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scap1643240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537742.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPA